          "body": "The border description in vv. 7-11 is legally precise and strategically revealing. The western boundary of Manasseh ran from Asher in the north, through Michmethath near Shechem, down to the Brook of Kanah — the natural ravine dividing Manasseh from Ephraim. The Mediterranean coast formed the western border; Issachar and Asher the east and north. Within this generous allotment, Manasseh also held enclaves in the territories of Issachar and Asher (v.11): Beth-shean, Ibleam, Dor, En-dor, Taanach, and Megiddo. These six cities are among the most strategically important in all of Canaan. Megiddo commanded the Jezreel pass — the gateway between the coastal highway and the Jordan Valley. Beth-shean guarded the Jordan Valley's northern entrance. Dor controlled the coastal trade route. That Manasseh was assigned these cities is a mark of covenantal generosity; that they would fail to take them (v.12) is among the most consequential failures in the entire distribution narrative."
