        "title": "The daughters of Zelophehad — bold faith that names the divine word and receives",
        "range": "17:3-6",
        "excerpt": "The LORD commanded Moses to give us an inheritance among our brothers. So according to the command of the LORD he gave them an inheritance among their father's brothers.",
        "body": "The scene in vv. 3-4 is one of the most legally and theologically precise moments in the entire book. Five women, daughters of a man who died in the wilderness leaving no male heir, appear before the highest authority structure in Israel — Eleazar the priest (representing the divine oracle, cf. Numbers 27:21), Joshua (representing covenantal leadership), and the leaders (representing tribal governance). Their claim is not personal appeal but biblical citation: 'The LORD commanded Moses to give us an inheritance among our brothers' (v.4).\n\nThe prior word they cite is Numbers 27:1-11, where the daughters had originally brought this same case before Moses, who brought it before the LORD, who ruled in their favor. The ruling was explicit: 'If a man dies and has no son, then you shall transfer his inheritance to his daughter' (Numbers 27:8). The daughters of Zelophehad are not innovating; they are remembering what God said and holding the covenant leadership accountable to it. This is the exact posture the New Testament commends in prayer — asking 'according to His will' (1 John 5:14), which means praying the promises back to God.\n\nJoshua's response is immediate and complete: 'according to the command of the LORD he gave them an inheritance' (v.4). No delay, no deliberation, no qualification. A prior divine word, accurately cited, produces a direct covenantal result. The daughters' names are recorded individually — Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, Tirzah — a mark of their covenant dignity and of the text's concern to honor their faith. The outcome in v.6 is striking: because the daughters received alongside the sons, Manasseh's total inheritance increased to ten portions. Their boldness enlarged the tribe, not diminished it.\n\nThe canonical significance extends beyond Israel's land distribution. These same daughters appear in Numbers 27, 36, and Joshua 17 — three separate confirmations that God's word about them held across the wilderness and the conquest. Calvin notes in his commentary on Numbers that God's attention to the daughters of Zelophehad demonstrates that the covenant's benefits are not bounded by human convention. The daughters received because they asked on the basis of what God had already said.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qarav* (they came near, v.4) — the verb used for approaching the presence of God, the altar, or the priest in a cultic context (Leviticus 9:5; Numbers 27:1). The daughters' approach is not casual petition but covenantal standing before divine authority. *Peh Yahweh* (the command/mouth of the LORD, v.4) — literally 'the mouth of the LORD,' the standard phrase for divine authoritative speech."
