        "excerpt": "But the sons of Manasseh could not take possession of these cities, because the Canaanites persisted in living in that land. It came about when the sons of Israel became strong, they put the Canaanites to forced labor, but they did not drive them out completely.",
        "body": "Verses 12 and 13 must be read together to expose their full meaning. Verse 12 appears to explain Israel's failure in terms of Canaanite tenacity — they 'could not take possession because the Canaanites persisted.' But v.13 immediately qualifies this: the problem was not permanent incapacity, because when Israel grew stronger, they were able to act — they simply chose to enslave rather than dispossess. The sequence reveals that 'could not' in v.12 is better understood as 'did not manage to,' not as a statement of permanent impossibility.\n\nThe strategic cities named in v.11 — Beth-shean, Ibleam, Dor, En-dor, Taanach, Megiddo — are among the most heavily fortified Canaanite city-states in Canaan. They commanded the major military and commercial arteries of the north. That Israel failed to take them is not surprising militarily; what is theologically decisive is that when strength arrived (v.13), Israel chose economic exploitation over covenant obedience. The term *mas* (forced labor) is the same word used for the corvée system Egypt imposed on Israel in Exodus 1:11. Israel, freed from *mas* in Egypt, now imposed *mas* on the Canaanites. The irony is severe.\n\nThe long-term consequences of this decision structure the entire book of Judges. Judges 1:27-28 repeats the list of cities Manasseh failed to take — almost verbatim from Joshua 17:11-12 — and confirms that forced labor was the outcome. Judges 2:1-3 announces the divine verdict: because Israel did not obey, the Canaanites 'will become as thorns in your sides and their gods will be a snare to you.' Douglas Moo, discussing the principle in his treatment of Romans 6:12-23, observes that retained sin always migrates from inconvenience to bondage. Manasseh retained the Canaanites for profit; by Judges and Kings, those retained Canaanites had become the very instruments of Israel's apostasy.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yakhol* (could not, v.12) — capacity verb, but context in v.13 shows the limitation was motivational rather than absolute. *Yarash* appears twice in v.13: once for the forced labor substitute and once for the dispossession that did not happen — the same verb used for two incompatible outcomes. *Mas* (forced labor) — the Exodus vocabulary of oppression, now turned around by Israel against its assigned enemies."
